Last-Blood Duel: MP3 players against cell phones
We will recommend how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
From this it is clear that it is best to buy only the phone.
Nevertheless, there are many reasons why we can obtain an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
Perhaps you would hardly buy yourself an expensive high-quality turntable to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
First of all, these musical products do not come out as LPs and from a qualitative point of view there is not even an objective reason for this.
However, if vinyls of hard-rock, jazz or blues probably flock to your shelves, a turntable like this at the very least you dream of it.
It also works with portable music, i.e. compressed music or simply in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to spend 8 thousand crowns on a reader, as a Pink Floyd fan perhaps hardly digests the twenty crown headphones of the market.
Two extremes among which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The battery life is the decision.
Some high-quality music players can do much more than just read music, but they don't even do cell phones by accident.
There is no other device as universal as the cell phone.
Next to the primary functions, phone and text, you can read music and videos, record both and have a camera, sometimes better sometimes worse and maybe even surf.
And if we consider smartphones and handhelds you will also have a miniature computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle that no refrigerator can make the grill and no television can photograph anything.
The universality of the cell phone also brings disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile phone and the sooner the indicator on the screen will require the charger.
And reading music consumes a lot of energy.
Few cell phones can read music for more than twelve hours, usually, and much less.
In this sense music players (especially the simplest ones) are much more effective.
As far as cheap phones are concerned, do not count that they can last for more than a few hours.
If you still add to it, from time to time, some calls, get another charger at work for safety, this also applies to the most expensive devices.
But you won't have this problem with an MP3 player, even the worst ones last at least 9 hours to continuous functionality with a charging.
A further problem exists when you download music into your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited part of the devices has the universal USB port and not all of them can be connected to the computer without special software.
Of course the music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few memory players are able to do it without adapter for minicards that are not used in mobile phones.
Readers, except for some exceptions (Ipod) do not need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from the computer.
Most mobile phones and readers create themselves a multimedia library ordered according to the names of the performers, album name, genre or user classification.
Some devices only reproduce the folder tree structure, similar to the Explorer tool in Windows, and some know how to do both things (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobile phones can do more.
When you choose a particular device you are especially interested in battery resistance, memory capacity, quality and type of audio outputs and clearly in ease of use.
If you need music especially from the background and if you listen to it every day only briefly on the tram you just need any mobile phone that reads MP3.
This now succeeds, clearly at any cell phone.
You don't have to worry too much about which formats your mobile phone or reader recognizes.
MP3 players support them all, the global majority of the music that comes to you will be in this format.
In addition to this format that belongs to the most popular, the total majority of devices support music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (format used by Apple and its Ipods).
The best mobile phones also allow, for example, to buy music online.
Just visit, through the mobile internet, the corresponding pages of the operator (or another provider) and buy the song or album.
This same service could already be a valid argument for buying a mobile-reader.
Unfortunately, the operators' offer is poor and is usually limited only to the hits of the moment of the radio.
The prices are not so low.
But it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (either via GSM, the internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their phones behind them.
Anyone who wants to listen to a little something rummages in their pocket while the MP3 player remains forgotten at home.
But it also depends on this, whether you always carry behind the headphones or at least the wireless earpiece.
If not, you can use the built-in player that almost every cell phone, but only a small portion of MP3 players, has.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of mobile-readers will be, for many, the price.
The cheaper ones normally cost less than 3,000 crowns.
For 3 and 4 thousand crowns you will already buy a very dignified walkman.
Usually, however, you will be limited by the absence of an input for common headphones.
The best and most technically equipped mobile phones and also with a 3.5 mm socket for common headphones, cost up to 15,000 crowns.
Instead, the reader’s advantage is, in addition to others, easy handling.
The simplest ones are not necessarily cheaper (see our choice) really anyone can handle them.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of manoeuvrability once with the common stereo or perhaps the turntable, is obvious.
There is no danger of accidentally hitting the startup of the mobile internet network and consequently of a giant bill for data transmission.
Which device to take
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have an exchangeable memory card slot (M2, microSD, etc.).
Also with regard to the purchase of the respective card, it falls within the 2 000 crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones can cope with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy an inexpensive MP3 player, take Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are a member of the most demanding listeners, preferably take specialized mobile phones - walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices feature individual MP3 keys and the convenience of the service thus approaching the same MP3 player.
In this area it has made more progress Sony Ericsson, which phones of the walkman line have the same scale of use as MP3 players sold separately.
The MP3 players of the above mentioned brands assure you the same service and price category up to 4 000 crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery strength (commonly 15 hours, in principle up to 35 hours).
The first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic as early as this year.
Maybe.
Perhaps the mobile market in the Czech Republic is mature enough and our operators offer virtually all services like their partners in Western Europe.
However, something is missing here – a virtual operator who forces traditional ones to lower the price.
Maybe he won't be missing for a long time.
Of the fact that Czech operators belong to the most expensive in Europe, we have already written many times on Mobil.cz.
At the end of the day, ČTÚ also confirmed it, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regularisation of roaming charges, perhaps a paradoxical situation will arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS will cost less from abroad than at home.
How can prices in the Czech Republic be kept so high in relation to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that would really like to start the fight.
Maybe it sounds crazy, even here we have three mobile networks and coverage highly above 100%.
On the other hand, mobile telophony operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this sense, the head of the Czech Telecommunications Council (ČTÚ) too, Pavel Dvoźk, who in the past has sometimes expressed that there is no room for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the traditional operator with his own network does not have many possibilities anymore. (It would be difficult to find other frequencies).
But there is still another possibility - the virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry into the market of virtual operators that led to a considerable drop in prices, to which traditional operators would have to react.
At the same time even before the entry of sharks such as Tesko Mobile and Virgin Mobile into the market, similar voices sounded in Britain as we did.
It has been shown, however, that the place for such operators is there and that they can be really successful.
At the end of the day, for example, we must not go very far.
In February of this year we informed you of the arrival of the Virtual Operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year this operator managed to win more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest local operator.
At the same time, behind Mobilking lies the Penta financial group to which U:fon belongs in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
In order to be able to actually work, it is enough for him, that is, many fewer customers than for a traditional operator.
They do not carry, i.e., relatively high expenses for the creation, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
Thus in the world virtual operators usually present themselves at low cost, offer calls and SMS at low prices, which is often in balance with the offer of the most restricted services
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS that costs at least half of its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, the bet on a target group can also be quite a good move.
This operator specifically points to men, so to speak.
"True men choose Mobilking operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO Mobile Entertainment Company that produces this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether we can affirm a similar concept as in Poland.
The press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepický doubted it: "The Czech market is relatively small for a fragmented approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of services it is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic no possibilities, say mobile network operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is ever an operator in the Czech Republic, Mobilking will not be.
"There is talk of the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic negotiations do not have much expectations.
The ignition of Mobilking will take place rather in the other countries of our area," said in a telephone dialogue for Mobile.cz Jana Studničková, the press spokesman for the Penta financial group.
Thus it has indirectly confirmed that current operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not very supportive of this view.
Rather, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor is created.
For some time now it has not hidden its interest in starting a virtual operator, the GTS Novera group that would like to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónika O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed services but also mobile telecommunications.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to advance in the negotiations with some of them," says the spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl group.
So maybe better times will come.
Unofficial information shows that the first virtual operator may have to have it by the end of the year.
For now, however, there is an impenetrable wall of silence around its creation.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very specific.
Until now no subject with a complex and serious project has addressed us," he mentioned in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň of the Telefònika O2 press section.
The Czech market is also characterised by other operators.
T-Mobil press spokesman Martina Kemrová adds in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "For now we have not noticed any viable and beneficial commercial projects for both of us, on which it is possible to continue building".
He adds: "In the T-Mobil network, a virtual operator will hardly appear by the end of the year.
At this moment we have already had to have a concrete agreement on the table, so that it could be considered on the horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on reaching its 3G license requests.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to the negotiations of potential virtual operators, especially in the context of sharing expenses and infrastructure.
Let us consider this, from the point of view of the customers, the most productive.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a common fast mobile internet network."
Competent authorities - with accomplices
The attitude of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to lower prices and thereby lower profits.
Why then facilitate the rise of such a competitor?
The nuisances around creation U:fon testify that when operators care about one thing they can row on the same side.
Perhaps the great pressure pressed against ČTÚ during the period of creation of U:fon towards the company of T-Mobile.
This is evidence of public access information from ČTÚ's web pages.
But right now, U:fon serves as an argument for not accepting the virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competition environment of the mobile market has been only a short while further enhanced with the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
With regard to the type of mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another competitor would place high demands on him and especially on his services."
However, the complete disinterest of the Czech regulatory bodies in the attitude of mobile operators is quite surprising.
It is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other developed countries - has no competence to interfere in economic competition.
That belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, has taken its typical position on the whole issue.
"The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of the contract for the rental of the necessary infrastructure between the mobile operator and the virtual operator had materialized.
No such contract has been concluded so far because the offer of potential buyers has probably not been interesting enough for traditional operators," said Kristián Chalupa, of the ÚOHS external relations section, in response to our question.
Such a statement by the representatives of the operators may not surprise us.
On the other hand, the office which must defend the interests of consumers and, above all, take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market is more than a delicate business.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Foreignly where virtual operators commonly work, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile services."
But obviously the pressure on the proper functioning of the market environment and the lowering of prices do not belong to the interests of ÚOHS.
Truly shocking throughout the situation is the almost exciting harmony of these three operators resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence arises on its own.
Just as the identical price of petrol for all petrol stations is undoubtedly the result of coincidence and competitive struggle.
"The section found no evidence of anti-competitive behaviour regarding this fact and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
No operator has a dominant position, so it does not have a corresponding greater responsibility for its conduct on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile network market for virtual operators may also be lacking telecommunications regulator," Chalupa mentioned in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
On such a market, of course, no Czech operator has a dominant position.
But some legal experts offer another approach - for the creation of a virtual operator the agreement of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has – at the end of the day logically – the monopoly of its network.
So for a certain portion it has to be dominant.
But even if we did not accept this argument, it should be a minimum warning for ÚOHS that three mobile operators should proceed in such a strangely similar way.
At the same time, complaints from interested parties (including the GTS Novera company mentioned above) show that there are very similar obstacles to trade with all operators.
Downloading responsibility to ČTÚ in telecommunications is a fairly frequent trick with which ÚOHS keeps itself out of the whole matter.
We have already seen this in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to promote the expansion of ČTÚ's rights in the field of economic competition in telecommunications until the recently adopted telecommunications law was updated, despite the fact that many experts expected the situation to improve.
The representatives of ÚOHS must know this more than well, but perhaps their interests are elsewhere.
It can be done when no one looks.
While we do not see how these pseudo-virtual operators work, some of them even exist in Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that publish their own price lists of mobile services but are only partially public.
Usually these are the companies that deal with multilevel marketing.
So for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and a number of others offer their mobile services.
The price lists of these companies usually reach only pre-established people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company towards the operator is a classic company customer, who orders a large amount of SIM card.
As an important customer then receives special price offers (and more).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar pre-sales.
"If the cases you are talking about, about which we will be interested, could be a breach of contractual conditions, and could lead to the conclusion of cooperation with this company," Martina Kemrová answered.
But it is rather unlikely that such an activity would not reach the ears of those responsible for mobile telephone operators.
Especially in the cases of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator at the same time defends itself from such an attitude.
In other words, the business of these companies derives a not indifferent profit and at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - they are not damaged in any way with their official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns about possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however only a small percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
They also have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name, so they cannot dispose in full of it as the usual customers of mobile telephone operators "
But this should be a bit strange at ČTÚ.
In addition, another issue opens up for ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such an attitude, why do they block the creation of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that ÚOHS has strong enough rights to expose similar activities and if it does not want to be satisfied with the explanation of the operators who have no idea of all this and that their commercial conditions forbid it.
When we're no longer expensive
As has already been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a significant drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where operators were born, traditional operators tried more or less to prevent their creation.
The arguments they used were practically identical - too small a market, too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But in developed countries, in these cases, the regulatory bodies have intervened to defend not mobile operators but their customers.
Both with the formal measures and with the non-formal pressure, then the creation of the first virtual operator was reached and others were agreed to him.
Unfortunately, Czech regulatory bodies launch from one to the other the whole case like a hot potato.
From our experience we cannot get rid of the feeling that the lack of clarity of skills in these cases makes it more than convenient.
But let's not throw in the towel.
If the background information is right and the virtual operator will really appear to us soon, the Czech mobile market will start again.
If one of the operators had agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, ÚOHS could hardly remain impassive of the refusal (discrimination) of the other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling at higher prices than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four new versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented in a solemn manner the new recordings of the national anthem "Kde domov můj".
The new recording of the anthem was made by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available – solo with male or female vocals, chorus pitch and instrumental edition.
The song is under the direction of Kateřina Knūnková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the revisions of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
On iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Already before he said on the radio "Český rozhlas" that he chose specifically to sing solo variants, the singers with the most representative young voices, who are expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I tried to take care that both and even the choir, have the clear diction, that the text is well understood, that they are in harmony," he reported.
Then the national anthem will celebrate next year's 175th anniversary.
The song "Kde domov můj" was first played in 1834 on the stage of the Stavovskéh divadlo in Josef Kajetán Tyl's original Fidlovačka opera accompanied by the music of František Škroupa.
It gained popularity and people spontaneously made it theirs.
The first stanza of the song after the founding of the Czechoslavakia of 1918 then became the natural part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the birth of the autonomous Czech Republic.
