On Wednesday MHD Prague will accompany you for the first time also with an electronic card
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be written in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date on which in the metro, tramway and bus will climb the first passengers who instead of the paper ticket will have in their pocket an electronic card.
At the moment they can get about one hundred thousand people who own their Opencard card.
Passengers can buy the 30- and 90-day and annual one (which will be valid from January 1, 2009) and at the same time be charged their card in the Infopoints and offices of the Transport Company and at Muzeum metro station, Můstek, Nádraź Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
You can buy coupons from yesterday on the Internet at the page of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred customers took advantage of the service before the afternoon.
Those who start using the internet service can completely forget the counters at metro stops where they had to make long lines for paper tickets so far.
The coupon is purchased via the internet and on the Opencard they recharge it on one of the twelve branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places passengers have at their disposal a desk with trained staff that will help those interested in the purchase on the internet and will also record on their card the credit acquired," said project spokesperson Martin Opatrný.
In addition to libraries it will be possible to load electronic coupons on the Opencards in ATMs and self-service which are installed at the entrances of the metro.
How are these ATMs?
They are red, resemble ticket obliterators and passengers have already noticed them at Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"There are now five throughout the city but by the end of the year there should be eighty," concluded Opatrný.
The coupon will be checked instead of by the driver by the ATM.
The ATM service that will run from tomorrow is very simple.
Just enter the Opencard card and after payment of the coupon, it will charge on top.
The electronic cards are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, in the urban lines of trains and buses from the number 300 to 499, which the inhabitants of the municipalities of Central Bohemia take to reach the capital.
"In added trains in Prague's integrated transport there are controllers equipped with card readers with whom they verify the temporal and zonal validity," explained Filip ticket control mode by the Ropid organisation, which develops the timetables for Prague's collective transport.
Urban buses have card readers integrated into the driver’s cash register.
During the ascent it is therefore necessary not only to show the magnetic card to the driver, but also to place the Opencard at the fixed point next to the cash register.
Thus the driver checks the validity of the coupons loaded.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the loaded coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this kind of information," Drápal added.
Passengers who take urban buses and do not remember, when the coupon expires, can go back to the self-service ATMs, where the coupons are loaded on paper.
Here you will see information on the validity of their documents on the device screen.
The Sudetian Germans wanted a referendum from the USA
The Sudetian Germans in 1945 asked to include Šumava in the United States.
This results from the letter deposited in the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the patronage of the United States.
With this wish, according to what is said, some groups of Sudetian Germans turned in 1945 to the President of the United States.
