Isabel Bayon rediscovers the sivilian essence of the dancer Tortola Valencia
A Seville dancer pays tribute to another equally Seville dancer.
Carmen Valencia Tortola, Catalan father (Florence Tortola Ferrer) and Andalusian mother (Georgena Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district, and at the age of three he moved with his family to London.
She was a free dance dancer and a specialist in oriental dances.
She led a fascinating life and was a pioneer of female emancipation, the likes of Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
He was Buddhist and vegetarian, and defended the cause for the abolition of the corset that prevented women from moving freely.
The life of this woman, who marked a revolution in dance and aesthetics in Europe between the two wars, has always fascinated Isabel Bayon.
"I would have liked to work with Pepa Gamboa and she proposed this character to me. I seemed incredible."
She supports the dancer: "We do not demand to tell her whole life, but to gather her spirit.
The titles of his dances have suggested to me some basic elements of flamenco.
Thus, "la danza de la mariposa" suggested me a guajira, or "la danza de la serpiente" some tango.
His dance was sensual and I was told that even my way of dancing is part of this aesthetic," he explains.
The staging includes two outstanding contributions: that of Miguel Poveda, who will sing Isabel again in one of his shows, such as the face in "La puerta abierta"; and that of the teacher Matilde Coral, who exceptionally wanted to work with what had been his pupil.
"Matilde plays Tortola as an adult, the character of maturity.
I am happy because he has agreed to work in my work and I feel very honored about this."
The set also includes the musical composition and guitarists such as Jesus Torres and Paco Arriaga, Miguel Ortega's singing, Pulga y Moi di Morón; El Pájaro's percussion, as well as Rafa La Viola's viola and the collaboration of an actor, Juanfran Juárez "who plays the role of eternal companion of these artists who have been divas to the full, and who have always had many suitors."
In the work is also present in some form the life of this woman that takes place in distant places, especially for that time, such as India, the United States or Russia, and then the whole of Europe, because, usually, she resided in London.
"I wanted to remember her, because I think she is one of the women who have had a huge influence in a given historical period and now no one remembers her and even less considers her work as something of value," says Bayon.
The show will begin today, at 8.30 p.m. at the theatre of Lope de Vega.
