Relapsed drivers of alcoholism will have to install the "alcoholock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires that drivers with three administrative penalties for excessive blood alcohol, install in his car the system that prevents driving the drunk vehicle or if you do not blow into the appropriate device.
The measure was announced last June and is already included in the annual report of the State Attorney General, according to which it will be a pilot project lasting one year.
The aim of this project is the reintegration of the driver, since he will have to attend a rehabilitation course on the road.
In addition to the Public Prosecutor General for Road Safety, the Directorate General for Traffic (DGT) and the Fondazione Istituto Tecnologico per la Safety dell'Automobile (FITSA) will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists reported more than once for drunk driving then returns to drive the car.
Alcoholock would avoid it, because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the rate of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow, or when a higher concentration of alcohol is detected than that allowed.
The cost is higher than 1000 euros and would be borne by the sanctioned person.
In this respect, a study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with such devices could reduce the infringements committed during the first year of introduction by up to 65%.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people a year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to curb these behaviours before they become criminal offences.
And to facilitate their development, since legal reform can be carried out on an ordinary basis, and, no doubt, the reform necessary for criminal proceedings would require organic law.
However, the device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial solution, although it has already been introduced experimentally in some industrial and public vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on a PSOE initiative in which it intends to install this system in school buses, as has already been done in France.
