Talking in your sleep
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very agitated to tell us something that happened to them the previous day, but to those children who speak while remaining asleep.
The first time that happens, at most you get a fright, but it doesn't really matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquium.
It occurs with a certain frequency, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely, most of you have been told that you spoke in your sleep.
This phenomenon can occur in a very sporadic way (once in life, for example associated with a high fever episode) or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single reason to explain this phenomenon.
Sometimes there are episodes related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night fears, night enuresis (weeing in bed), or sleepwalking, but not necessarily so.
As mentioned above, it may be associated with very high fever stages, situations of stress or overexcitement.
In any case, it is still a phenomenon that has not been studied.
The intensity with which it appears is also extremely variable.
It can happen that the person speaks with a very quiet tone of voice, with loose words, almost in a whisper or that the opposite happens (screams, screams, long speeches ...).
In cases where the event is particularly intense, it would be appropriate to observe the child and possibly consult a specialist to check if there is any issue that is generating an abnormal state of anxiety as an outlet to the situation.
We have said that this is a benign alteration so there is no treatment unless it is associated with other sleep disorders that can be treated (for example, if coupled with insomnia or stress situation).
What can be done, on the other hand, is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before he goes to sleep.
Propose quiet games and avoid programs or television series that arouse fear or suggest violence.
With very nervous children for whom it is tiring to relax, you can use relaxation techniques to help them acquire some inner calm.
This will allow the child to sleep more quietly.
Once the sonniloquies appear try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day they will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not aware of what's going on, and you'd disrupt his sleep.
Although he's talking, he's asleep, so he's resting.
Remember that if he appears very distressed and the episodes have a certain frequency it is better to consult a doctor or check where such great anxiety comes from in the child.
If you understand what it says (which is not the most common situation), do not fall into the temptation to question him for information.
You will get nothing, because he is asleep and therefore unconscious to organize his thought.
In addition, you are able to hear what he says but not to see what he is dreaming to say, so you have to pay close attention to the interpretation of the information and to the conclusions to which these could lead.
