The meeting - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday the tenth anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr FrancineDécary, had every reason to rejoice, as Héma-Québec has become one of the most secure and effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence, seriously shaken by the scandal of infected blood in the years between 1980 and 1990.
As we know, the national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were infected with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C in the 1980s.
Faced with such a tragedy and population protests, the government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public investigation, led by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to the spread of recommendations to prevent the recurrence of such a disaster.
While Judge Krever was late to draw up a report, some provinces set up a committee with the aim of designing a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, this mandate was carried out by the Gélineau Committee.
Following the Gélineau et Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Québec and Société canadienne du sang (Canadian Blood Society) for all other provinces and territories.
In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, just 38% of people said they still had confidence in the donations system in Québec, recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was mortifying.
Thanks to continued efforts to improve the safety of blood samples and field research over the following years, we have regained public confidence," he explains before saying proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary is convinced that "confidence is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, there were numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new manifestation of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which has been the president since 1998, the year of the foundation.
"And we absolutely did not know if that disease could be transmitted through infected blood.
It was therefore based on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélinau reports, that when doubts arise and a serious illness may arise, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself with a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, is taken with exclusion measures.
In April 1999, the blood of those who had spent more than a month in the United Kingdom since 1980 was rejected.
Now, for a few years, it has been shown that this disease is no doubt transmitted through infected blood.
This episode thus showed us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle."
In 1999 a much more efficient technique for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow the presence of the virus in donors' blood to be recognized directly and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which instead the tests used until then were based.
The TANs have allowed the window period to be reduced, i.e. from the moment the person contracted the disease to the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood thanks to our techniques, explains the specialist.
That period could be reduced to less than one week.
The risk of ignoring the presence of infected donors and of not being able to detect them has thus decreased considerably.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS with a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood samples will have to be distributed before anyone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 000 and 500 000 blood samples each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmitted with a transfusion occurs.
I believe that today one can feel calm in receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health, says the head of the Héma-Québec management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than a year ago the Chikungunya virus appeared on Réunion Island, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted in the blood by an insect.
"We must be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary before pointing out that in addition to having secure resources, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient resources.
"Needs increase as the population ages.
Because cancer treatment is more aggressive, patients often need a supply of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the number of donors, which on average accounts for only 3% of the Québec population acceptable as donors."
However, all healthy people who are 18 years of age and meet eligibility criteria may donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer themselves as donors are not accepted, because they are affected by AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where the latter is widespread, they will be rejected for a period of one year.
"With this 3% we manage to maintain an inventory capable of responding to the needs of hospitals.
Shortcomings are very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this group of donors as they grow older and can no longer make donations.
Now it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but above all to restrain them and incite them to become regular donors.
Nowadays life is so frenetic that it is hardly an hour to donate blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec distributes not only blood samples, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, eye globes and skin heart valves that are used almost exclusively for severe burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being deposited with Héma-Québec which operates the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, which was once considered a biomedical waste, abounds in blood rich in stem cells that can serve to cure serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the insertion in the bank of our thousandth sample of cordon blood and we plan to take more than a thousand each year.
You should start proposing them for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary who describes this practice of collecting cordon blood as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot have access to it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
