Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to ruin anyone who dares to stand up for a position contrary to his.
No matter the outcome of the trial, writers and publisher of the book Canada Nero will have to spend a large amount of money in order to organize their own defense and fight, with decidedly unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers financed from practically bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Moreover, in these fights with unequal weapons, the tactic is often to ruin the defendant in order to impose a consensual regulation that gag the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to rule on the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is before the public that it should have presented its own vision of the facts.
Contrary to what happens in many countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada usually take place with the exchange of views and not with batons.
It would have been sufficient for the company to open its books, its documents, and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of teams of independent researchers who could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to have too much confidence in public opinion and reluctantly rejects petitions and letters in support of the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can ask for a "public" debate when his contempt for that same audience is clearly evident?
