Operation - rescue for Wall Street – Dialogue between Republicans and Democrats
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, representatives of the Republican and Democratic deployment, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the greatest plan for saving-finance after the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the US $700 billion plan, which aims to curb the financial crisis that has been hanging over Wall Street for months, has yet to be ratified by the two chambers of Congress.
In particular, it provides for: verifications of its effective implementation by elected leaders, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money, new provisions to contain the number of homes for which no payments have been made, as well as a right of inspection on remuneration paid to managers of protected companies.
The American Secretary to the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the President of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiation marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an effective agreement on markets," said Bush administration representative, Henry Paulson.
"Every decision was taken in such a way as to safeguard the American economy and people from the current crisis on Wall Street.", the Democrat explained.
"It's the crucial point: if we hadn't acted in this way, invaluable discomforts and upsets would have spilled on the daily lives of Americans," declared Republican Judd Gregg.
The conclusion of the negotiations was marked by concerns about the impact of a new failure on investors.
The time limit granted corresponded to the opening of the markets this morning.
United later in the negotiations, the two candidates for the American presidentials showed rather favourable to the agreement, but did not avoid expressing their discontent before the adoption of extreme solutions.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama deserves the credit of adding some provisions to the agreement, in particular the one that will allow the owners to keep their homes and the one relating to wages for the managers of companies covered by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of others, there is nothing to rejoice about.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on the screen of American TV.
Interviewed on another channel to know if he will vote in favour of the plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to analyze the details, but I hope so."
"As far as I've read, it's something that we all have to digest and that will allow us to move forward."
The option of non-intervention is simply unacceptable," he said.
The 700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money the dubious, risky and unsaleable assets of American financial institutions.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis due to the outbreak of a real estate bubble that led first of all to the collapse of risk mortgage loans (borrowers) , and then extended to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of liquidity and the disbandment of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of incumbent Republicans who blew up the first draft agreement last week.
It seems to have emerged from that dead end since Democrats accepted that the active "toxic" of some companies in difficulty is only protected by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to meet everyone, in Congress, a provision has been added that, if the government were to cope with losses over the five years to come due to this programme, it could impose new taxes in order to maintain its own balance.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion to which 100 billion can still be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of 350 billion is expected to be ratified by a further vote of Congress.
In exchange for his help, Washington will obtain shares in the protected companies that will receive dividends in the event of a profit and that will be able to resell when the waters have calmed down.
According to the plan, the Federal Government will have the opportunity to delay the foreclosure procedures relating to real estate loans and to set limits on remuneration and starting allowances paid to the managers of the companies involved.
Starting today, the architects of the plan would like to submit him to the vote of the House of Representatives, and to the vote of the Senate on Wednesday.
