What was produced in the Zuschlag & Associates Invoice Factory?
Soon, on October 8, the hearing of the criminal trial against János Zuschlag and its members will be discussed.
The political man and his associates are accused of repeated commercial fraud committed within the framework of a criminal association which has caused considerable damage, and of other offences, including forgery of documents.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office the money obtained from competition notices, was used by them for private purposes, and they have often certified the carrying out of activities through false invoices.
State and municipal money, a total of 65 million florins, ended up partly in the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal organization, partly in the pockets of some people.
According to the method, announced by the investigating authorities, they took the money obtained from calls for tender on the basis of invoices for non-existent transactions and the associations never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the accuser act most of the invoices were false.
To do so, the invoice blocks were purchased at the market in Józsefváros, the circular stamps instead were manufactured in Kiskunhalas.
And to decide on behalf of which firms to issue invoices, it was established among other things during the trip through the hills over the Balaton where János Zuschlag had sent István Lados.
According to the latter's confession he had to choose pensions and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for the consummations, along the lines of these then were prepared invoices to be forwarded to the calls for competition, among others, to those of the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs and the City of Budapest.
Most of these are the work of István Lados and András İri, who, according to our information, has drafted the reports needed to obtain the funding.
One of the choices of Lados' "travel studies" was a brewery.
According to two invoices issued by Zuschlag and members in 2003, the restaurant provided meals for a group of 90 people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
So many people, however, according to the restaurateur, would not all join the premises together.
Similarly, the bill issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later called Együtt in Harmadik Évezredert, is full of formal errors and content.
A guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj has only three rooms, more than 10 people could not stay there, however the invoice included 130 guests.
But the compilers of the invoices full of imagination exaggerated when they signaled Pigal Kft., also this one deals with catering, in whose accounts - according to the information issued to the judicial authorities - did not even include the documents on behalf of the companies Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the company's director, told hvg.hu that when he was summoned to the prosecutor's office and showed him the invoices, he immediately realized that they were fake documents.
"On the stamp the name and the VAT match of our enterprise were at a wrong place."
He added: in addition to the formal reasons, the fact that according to the invoice 100 people were accommodated, when in total they have eleven rooms and there are not so many beds.
Moreover the invoice was catering and their restaurant is no longer in operation for a long time.
Assiduous invoice compilers did not bother to inform themselves that the Budapest travel agency of their choice, organizes only trips abroad, so they foolishly indicated on the invoice with payment in cash trips to Hungary, which did not agree with the company's bill issuing practice.
In addition, as shown during the survey, VAT was also shown on the invoice, while travel to countries outside the European Union is exempt from VAT.
Among other things, the amount of VAT was also incorrect on the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. in favour of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, in fact on the services offered by the company you have to apply the VAT to 15% and not 25% as indicated on the invoices, moreover the employees of the hotel issued only printed invoices, while the invoice was made by hand.
In addition to this, the "emittances" have ruined other invoices, in the case of a company they have indicated as carried out the transport of goods by road, as is known from the proceeding of the Public Prosecutor, activity that was not carried out by the company founded originally for advice of investments.
Also for formal defects - due to non-compliant invoice format, false stamp - it was found that invoices issued in favour of Együtt in Harmadik Évezredert Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont are false.
The same happened in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Field, whose representatives denied having issued the invoices in question.
The falsifiers did not even pay attention to the fact that the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in liquidation when (2001) a group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület had lunch there, precisely for this reason the curator of the liquidation of the company, according to our information, denied having issued that invoice.
They made invoices knowingly
Another group of invoices issuers consists of those who were aware of having to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány foundation issued an invoice at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták in favour of the Együtt foundation in Armageddon Évezredert of nearly 4 million florins.
Ludovic Györfi, one of the defendants, according to the accusation, persuaded the director of Collab Kft. to issue fictitious invoices.
Biogate Kft also cooperated with Zuschlag and its partners in liquidation, which in 2003 provided invoices issued for a value of approximately 5 million florins to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület association, behind which there was no real economic activity.
Not even movement of money because the invoices prepared were then reversed, but the associations forgot to make this aspect appear in their own documents.
In the following group of companies issuing invoices belong those who are connectable with the defendants.
For example, Ivan Kubatov, authorized to the address of the general manager of Delta Trió Kft, based in Budapest but not available there, who deals with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles.
The company issued several invoices in October, November and December 2005 relating to the sale of computer equipment, worth about 18 million florins.
According to the data of the investigation Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas under liquidation from September 14, 2005 purchased these invoices.
The general manager of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov would forward the company documents between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov, during the investigation, acknowledged that he issued invoices on behalf of the company to Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt companies in Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and the countervalue was taken from him.
At the express request of Ivan Kubatov Romanian masons founded the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
