At the request of the co-defendant lawyer Zsolt Szente, editor of the company's founding documents, invoices were issued in the name of the companies to the associations related to Zuschlag: the Atlasz and the Y-Generáció.
On behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade Kubatov issued 15 invoices to the various institutions for a total value of 14.2 million guilders.
The prosecutor considers that Kubatov has pocketed 10% of the amounts indicated on the invoices, as well as the VAT.
The man also used Szi-Beri Bt. to issue fictitious invoices, manufactured for Biztos Pont's call for competition.
Y-Generáció and Szövetség at Modern Magyarországért in January 2006 submitted a call for the Socialist Party's public utility body, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They also won 500,000 florins each but the sums were not used for the purposes indicated in the ban.
In order for this not to come out, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft have been submitted to TMA.
These invoices were found during the search of Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing some of the defendants, as they have already done in the prosecutor's office, will probably report on the development of the production of invoices.
However, the most interesting thing could be if defendant number one, János Zuschlag, would decide to lift the veil over everything.
His confession so far has not been very detailed and although he has repeatedly promised to talk about everything extensively, he has not yet done so.
We must see if it is in your interest, it may also be that the socialists have made agreements with Zusi, who - in exchange for compensation of 50 million guilders, much of the damage - would be willing to make the scapegoat.
Zuschlag could have been offended by the fact that his demands to lighten his prison conditions, that is, the granting of house arrests, have not so far been fulfilled.
While the perpetrators of indemnifiable commercial offences and causing much greater damage can freely walk or at least wait at home for the end of the proceedings against them, which is not granted to him.
The psychology of excessive bidding: why spend more money?
At auctions buyers are inclined to spend more, to overestimate the goods.
Neurologists and research economists at the University of New York have been able to discover the neuro-economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study appeared in Science magazine men do not want to stay back in a race such as eBay auction, so they are also available to pay a higher price.
Research has tried to trace the nervous pattern of this "game" at the level of the nervous system through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lotto, the other group of players participated in an auction while using the functional magnetic resonance imaging method (fMRI) they examined the active areas of the brain of the people participating in the experiment.
In both games the participants could win some money, but in the auction game, in which the substantial element is to licitate more than the other, the striated body under the cerebral cortex intensively enters into operation when losing to the game.
This brain area, in addition to other functions, plays a role in the "self-gratification" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to researchers, the price rise is explained by avoiding the vehement reaction of the striated body.
To support their theory, research group economists carried out a financial pursuit investigation.
In this investigation, three groups contested a partner under different conditions.
They reported to the control group what the real value of the product in question was and they placed their bet.
Another group in addition to this have promised that in the case of winning they will receive another $15 prize.
The third group would instead receive $15 before the auction, but the members of the group would lose the money in case of auction loss.
The difference between the two groups consisted in the fact that for one of them the win was emphasized, while for the other the loss.
Countering the neurologist hypothesis, members of the group who played "against loss" were willing to make higher bets than the control group or "winning".
"These results are not deductible from any of the previously existing economic theories.
These, in fact, so far explained the phenomena found at auctions with the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Only the methods of creating the neurological image helped solve the contradiction between the two theories, so that we came to a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to seek medical attention?
Almost half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver diseases are mentioned among the first causes of death.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients amounts to one hundred thousand, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know they are infected.
The definition of hepatitis is the collective name of contagious liver diseases caused by several viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms, typical are hepatitis and jaundice, but their pathogens and the diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread into two main forms depending on the pathogen: hepatitis A and E via the food channel (e.g. water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal leakage, saliva).
For those traveling it is useful to immunize against the A and B virus, against the C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After yellowish spots are formed on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the stools become clear and the urine dark, the healing takes place within two to three weeks.
One million people die every year worldwide from hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, which causes liver tumors and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason is, according to estimates, that only one in ten people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver tumors.
Most infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because pathogens degrade their liver cells in a subtle way, in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore it is very important to prevent and perform regular medical tests.
This disease is much more frequent than average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattoos.
In the world to date the number of people infected with chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since a routine laboratory examination also reveals the disease it is worth asking your family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so it ceases infectious power and can be prevented the formation of tumors.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 worldwide by associations of patients.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic viral hepatitis, the causes of its development and early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God feels less pain?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith functions as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Oxford University scientists performed an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
As part of the somewhat bizarre investigation, an electroshock was carried out to 12 Catholic believers and to as many atheists, while everyone observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploration technique of the human brain it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for pain control.
The test is the first in a series of research in which in addition to academics also take part scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University.
The test took place exactly this way: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
Researchers asked participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrato and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci's ermine painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary originated a sort of religious state among believers, while Leonardo's painting was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and they considered it to have a tranquilizing effect.
The subjects of the experiment spent half an hour in front of the MRI scanner and in this time aro received 20 electroshocks in four consecutive series, while observing either the religious theme painting or the other.
Catholics reported that the vision of the Virgin Mary made them feel "safe", as if "someone took care of them" and "were calmed down and were pervaded by peace".
Looking at the religious-themed image, they accounted for 12% less pain than when Leonardo's work was before them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who took part in the test himself, believes that such a result can be achieved with any image with a strong effect even for atheists, but you have to find the right image.
"We need to look for an image to which they have very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father," said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright welcomed the result of the research.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it can change our personality." - added Wright.
After the excellent results only the question remains if the painting of a Madonna by Leonardo or another painter of similar caliber is presented to believers, what effect could it have on the control of pain?
Would the vision of a quality virgin Mary bring better results?
You're what you say about yourself
On the tenth birthday day Google can claim to be in people's pockets as well as in the sky above their heads; it knows where they spent their holidays, which clinic they attend and what they care about.
However, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the company's directors, this is not enough yet.
What concerns the skeptics who compare with the Orwellian nightmare, they just don't see the substance of web 2.0.
Recently Eric Schmidt told the Financial Times that Google's main purpose is to collect as many personal data as its users and this is necessary to stick to the original goal of Google's founders that it was: "we put all the information in the world into a system!".
According to the Google director interviewed the company, after 10 years of revolutionary work, it is still at the beginning of being able to handle all the information.
When asked what will happen in five years Schmidt answered: he would like if Google could answer questions like "what do I do tomorrow?" or "what would be the right job for me?", but software can't answer seemingly simple questions because they don't know enough about users.
Not all internet users are aware that during their internet searches, exactly the words you search are recorded, from which IP address they are searched for and on which page the interested parties stop after the search.
Through the Personalized Search started two years ago users e.g. can store their browsing history, may relate what they searched and clicked, these then in the long run will generate much better tailored results; on this same logic is based Recommendations with which the system offers us products and services based on our preferences declared and recorded previously.
What happens if my data is used against me, if they look at what I do? - concerned users are wondering about Google's data monopoly.
In most cases, the counter-reactions of the internet users are caused by the fear of the size of the potential power represented by the company, and not by the sense of guilt, by the fear of punishment, by the desire for freedom or even by the rebellion against power.
One fact is confirmed, however, that all the expressions sought are not only recorded but in justified cases they can also be provided to third parties, in such legal cases nothing defends the personal rights of internet users.
The most striking example of this in recent times has perhaps been the coordinated action against Brazil's paedophiles, in which Google has forwarded to the Brazilian government the information that has made possible the identification of paedophiles from the Orkut community page maintained by Google.
Internet users worried about personal rights instead sighed of relief in May when the company - in agreement with the electronic legal protection association EFF - successfully demonstrated the truth in court against the FBI: not even later can Google be forced with no point of the constitution to provide any information secretly requested by the FBI.
(At the same time the federal government successfully snatched nearly 50,000 web addresses and a thousand search expressions obtained in reference to the confirmation of the child protection law passed years earlier, but however failed to obtain the search lists of individual users and the entire list of web pages and keywords dating back to two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore rather contradictory: those who fear to provide their personal data are pushing Google because they believe that this undermines their intimate sphere and private life by starting to use its services and rising up with the rebellion of multinationals that stand out for the conservative image.
Meanwhile the American geek culture and the proliferation of fans, activists and computer users appeared in many countries see in them the future generation of big companies, the "cool corporation", as opposed to their rival, the Microsoft liquidated as the conqueror of the world because of Windows, although both fought for the same goal.
This can happen because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for their services, the source code kept up to date and the program package is much more accessible, youthful and cool than the official software giant practice.
But it can also happen because geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between personal rights and the internet, which implies just one of the most often repeated keywords in recent years, web 2.0.
Web 2.0 speaks of nothing but collaboration, intentionally leaving traces behind us and exploiting the communication channels at our disposal and while the size of these changes for each individual, the substance is the same: to show ourselves.
A young average can create profiles in multiple community pages, from Facebook to Xanga, can connect them with other services such as Twitter or last.fm that lists his or her musical tastes, all of these can insert them into systems such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm, can also write blogs on which his latest photo galleries are automatically stored on Flickr or Picasa.
Meanwhile, we read of numerous exemplary cases from which it is clear that the girl, seeing the series of photos taken in the morning from the common tour of friends, easily learns with whom she spent the night her treacherous boyfriend or a company can fire one of its employees because she has written a sincere opinion on the company summit: one thing is sure, the concept of private life has now completely reconsidered.
