The intelligent machine imitates the bumblebee's flight
What could be the best way to develop anti-collision technologies if not to imitate sensors of obstacles in nature?
For example, bees.
In the amazing project presented to CEATIC in Japan, the bumblebees gave the initial strategic cue to Nissan engineers on how to build the next generation of anti-collision systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built the biomimetic robot BR23C, a robotic mini-auto with the properties of bees, with the final aim of creating a system able to avoid all collisions.
Flying the bees form their own oval personal space that looks very much like our protective shield - explained Kazuhiro Doi, director of the field of PR technologies and research and development.
Important is the role of the bee's view, capable of a 300 degree view in every direction.
Engineers drew on the telemetric laser idea to copy the bee's view function.
The BR23C detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius, calculates the distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor that immediately transforms it into a command to avoid collision.
In a fraction of a second the robot perceives the obstacle and then, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction turning the wheels of the necessary measure to avoid the accident.
This avoiding maneuver, in a different way from the current system, takes place in an entirely instinctive way.
"If it weren't, the robot car wouldn't be able to react quickly to avoid collisions," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and auto robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately because this technology corresponds to the damaging and inner layer of the protective shield, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to avoid the other bees.
This process must take place in the blink of an eye.
But unlike bees the deviation cannot go up or down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and in the steering direction of the wheels.
In this way instead of the endless possibilities available to bees to avoid the other bees, the robot, as a possibility available, can rotate on itself, accelerate and slow down.
The BR23C is powered by batteries to lithium polymers, lighter and with high energy density, which means that their duration is longer than those to lithium ions.
According to Andoh, the instantaneousity of the intelligent reaction is important, not data processing or even less the ability to store them.
This robot has to process some inputs in seconds and react.
There is no need to store and react with intuitive logic based on previous manoeuvring data, so it only uses a memory of a few dozen Kb.
You don't need a gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step towards the development of a technology for the immediate avoidance of collisions that are expected at Nissan, within 10 years it can be installed on standard vehicles.
Further possibilities for application can be represented by the unification with the GPS satellite navigation system which avoids obstacles on the road leads to destination.
