The elites in danger
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago with the House of Representatives vote against the $700 billion bailout plan launched by the White House: a significant part of Americans was, and is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the economy.
The New York Times of yesterday confirms this by informing us that the current crisis is breaking the Republican Party, increasingly divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, instead, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and the world of finance, strong especially in the States of Central and South.
The soul, in fact, that became overwhelmingly alive with the vote of which I said at the beginning.
However, this is just one example of the changes, the great changes, which the current economic earthquake perhaps heralds or already shows: not only in the United States but throughout the West and perhaps not even here alone.
Both in the US and in Europe, the crisis seems to function as an incubation accelerator for a long time that in the new climate solidifies and finally comes to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-realization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category State-sovereignity in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, yes, have deep ties with foreign countries, but which first of all see the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state, very much involved.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: namely how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people and families who, among other things, are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically world-wide but politically it is almost exclusively national.
Political internationalism seems fundamentally out of the question or not to have much to say: the clear evidence is that the European Union, divided as usual between the different interests and between the different state strategies, fails to decide any common political line.
And so it is from the government of every single state that everyone expects interventions, rescue and revival plans, new rules, and above all the provision of funds: since when we get to grips it is only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources that can try to put things back together.
And they also have the necessary means and the right to use them: two resources of immeasurable value, in certain circumstances, of which no market and no international organization will probably ever be able to dispose to a similar extent.
This new emphasis that the crisis places on the state-national element is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the increasing importance that the most recent developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor very closely linked to that element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of the increasingly sophisticated technology, of the immaterial, while we were convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future will have to deal more and more with those very little immaterial things that are water, crops, oil.
All things that, look a little bit, can certainly be transported from one place to another of the earth but are still absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So that those who are sovereign, certainly have several more cards than those who are not, to those who have the misfortune to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I come to the second new feature, however, that foresaw a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand the awareness of the objective need for authoritative leadership, the request of someone who knows how to take control of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leaders, economic species, proved so inadequate and full of shadow zones.
And together something even deeper and in a certain sense disturbing: a discredit, an intolerance, an image of inadequacy, a sense of distance, which tends to involve the entire ruling class in an increasing number of Western countries.
In other words, the conviction seems to grow more and more, in vast sectors of the population, that before their actions are the same ideas as the social elites so far in vogue, their way of feeling and being, their culture in the overall sense of the term, to have made their own time and to be increasingly foreign to the opinions of majorities.
The demand for leadership, in short, subterraneanly feeds a branched but powerful movement of delegitimization of the traditional ruling classes and political arrangements, which manifests itself in the sudden "revolts" election or in the sudden turn of the collective moods of these last and very recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria-Bavaria to the collapse of Labour consensus in Britain, to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps even the victory of the right in Italy has something to do with it).
There is the impression that traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their formats would say someone, make it increasingly difficult to understand, and therefore to represent, what is not taking shape from today in the deep strata of Western societies and that the economic crisis reinvigorates, increases, potentially shakes to an extent.
In the face of all this, talking about a 'rebellion of the masses' on the agenda would be frankly exaggerated.
But keeping your eyes open is certainly not for nothing.
