When the energy comes from the waves now the big ones fall into the field
It is an exterminated field, which occupies over 70% of the planet's surface and is now being discovered by the world's largest energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which they have put their eyes, and now they try to put their hands, giants like Chevron.
The possibility of obtaining energy from sea movements has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil dropped, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmentalists and the new rise in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity needs could be covered by sea wave exploitation plants.
This would be twice as much as the amount currently produced by nuclear power stations.
And in addition there would be currents and tides.
Colossi on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced it seemed a revolutionary step.
Two years later they are increasingly betting on marine energy and among these companies have always been devoted to traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies - said the spokesperson for a subsidiary company to the US oil giant at the Wall Street Journal economic newspaper - and is considering cooperating with us".
The cooperation in question concerns obtaining a permit from the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a marine energy exploitation project in Alaska.
It is a very good signal, especially considering that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and President Bush recently started a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to cover the road of energy that comes from the sea and the sums invested so far, as not known in the details, indicate an increasing interest according to observers.
Technology to be developed.
Experts talk about a technology still in its infancy, also because marine energy does not escape all doubts about the environmental impact.
For now, plants such as Portugal or some in Scotland are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
In order to produce large-scale energy, however, technologies with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the choices are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys connected to each other.
The thrust of the waves, which causes the buoys to move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure by pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
Pressure runs a turbine that in turn powers a generator.
The electricity is sent ashore through submarine cables.
For now there are four plants of this type being designed, waiting only for federal approval and part of the energy could serve for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a mall and a parking lot using six submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The movement of water when there are tides rotates the blades of the turbines, creating a rotary movement that feeds a generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permissions to take advantage of the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they tell the Institute for the research of electricity, deserves at this moment the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as an energy source.
It is precisely on the energy of the tides that states like that of New York, Maine and Alaska, along with others bordering on the coast, have already invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and previewed investments up to 35 million for 2009.
